<text>&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0//EN" "http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-html40/strict.dtd">
&lt;html>&lt;head>&lt;meta name="qrichtext" content="1" />&lt;style type="text/css">
p, li { white-space: pre-wrap; }
&lt;/style>&lt;/head>&lt;body style=" font-family:'.SF NS Text'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:400; font-style:normal;">
&lt;p style=" margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;">Article 6&lt;/p>
&lt;p style=" margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;">This article of the Act is focused on presenting the alleged humanitarian aspects of the European scramble for African territories. Most notably, there is a call here for the European powers to ensure the preservation of the native peoples. This included, significantly, the suppression of any and all slavery that they encountered. This clause also emphasises that Christian missionaries who visited these African territories would be given special protections to assist them in their righteous evangelical missions. Surprisingly, perhaps, alongside this was the guarantee of religious toleration and freedom of worship. This article in particular helped the act gain public acceptance.&lt;/p>
&lt;p style="-qt-paragraph-type:empty; margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;">&lt;br />&lt;/p>&lt;/body>&lt;/html></text>
