&lt;p style=" margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;">Chapter VI&lt;/p>
&lt;p style=" margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;">This is the part of the Act that is known as the Principle of Effective Occupation. This states that the European powers could acquire the rights over colonial lands, only if they had ‘effective occupation’ of them. This could be presented as treaties with local leaders, if a European flag was flying, or if they established a policed administration system in the territory. This was not just significant in clarifying how a European territory could take control, but it was essential in determining the limitations of their territories. In this sense, it was another form of reducing possible tensions between European imperial powers.&lt;/p>
&lt;p style="-qt-paragraph-type:empty; margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;">&lt;br />&lt;/p>&lt;/body>&lt;/html></text>
